00:29:42.782 --> 00:29:45.482
I just wondering if you have any investigations to show that

500
00:29:46.102 --> 00:29:48.062
it is mediated by that

501
00:29:49.022 --> 00:29:52.862
three specific positive charged amino acids, or just because of

502
00:29:52.922 --> 00:29:56.742
the decreased less positive charge. Thank you.

503
00:29:58.402 --> 00:30:00.782
Well, to your question, there is actually...

504
00:30:01.142 --> 00:30:04.542
I guess those question are integrated, right?

505
00:30:04.642 --> 00:30:07.422
So it's either the number of charge or that specific charge.

506
00:30:08.182 --> 00:30:09.852
Our structural modelings

507
00:30:11.282 --> 00:30:15.122
inform that RNA seems to most likely engage with that

508
00:30:15.142 --> 00:30:18.182
particular region, but it's also a very large region.

509
00:30:18.262 --> 00:30:22.222
So we chose the 3A residues because we

510
00:30:22.262 --> 00:30:26.062
wanted to minimally impact other known function of ENL so that we

511
00:30:26.102 --> 00:30:28.622
can isolate RNA binding effect, but that's a good point.

512
00:30:29.622 --> 00:30:29.942
All right.

513
00:30:30.102 --> 00:30:31.982
Okay. I said the last question, but let's do one more over here.

514
00:30:32.242 --> 00:30:32.482
All right.

515
00:30:32.682 --> 00:30:35.322
Thank you. Excellent talk. Thank you. I learned a lot.

516
00:30:35.662 --> 00:30:36.782
My question is,

517
00:30:37.802 --> 00:30:41.142
using the inhibitor or the mutation of ENL,

518
00:30:41.622 --> 00:30:45.422
it also, in fact, that the function is

519
00:30:45.522 --> 00:30:49.498
the proteinperceive? How we can

520
00:30:49.598 --> 00:30:53.378
explain it is the condensates change

521
00:30:53.478 --> 00:30:57.258
per se is not the related abundance or

522
00:30:57.318 --> 00:30:59.378
the protein function itself.

523
00:30:59.938 --> 00:31:02.848
Right. That's a good question. In these cases,

524
00:31:02.958 --> 00:31:06.888
the compound is not designed

525
00:31:06.918 --> 00:31:08.978
to dissolve the condensate specifically.

526
00:31:09.008 --> 00:31:12.598
I think this is really based on our extensive work to

527
00:31:12.638 --> 00:31:16.258
demonstrate a condensate formation at HOX string is very important.

528
00:31:16.318 --> 00:31:20.018
So this small molecule inhibitor is basically trying to say, "Okay, if that

529
00:31:20.138 --> 00:31:23.918
structure is important, if we can displace that structure, does it

530
00:31:23.978 --> 00:31:25.478
have a consequence?" So

531
00:31:26.398 --> 00:31:30.118
I acknowledge the specific inhibitor is not designed to

532
00:31:30.138 --> 00:31:33.748
dissolve the condensate, but this actually demonstrate that

533
00:31:33.758 --> 00:31:37.558
beyond dissolving condensate, there's other way to target condensate as

534
00:31:37.598 --> 00:31:41.238
well, such as making them coming off the chromatin. Thank you.

535
00:31:41.278 --> 00:31:42.098
Thank you.

536
00:31:42.198 --> 00:31:42.428
Thanks.

537
00:31:42.978 --> 00:31:46.608
Thanks, Liling. Just a really fantastic mechanistic discussion, and I

538
00:31:46.618 --> 00:31:49.638
think really illustrates how the field is advancing.

539
00:31:49.958 --> 00:31:53.698
With that, we want to transition to a true pioneer in the

540
00:31:53.758 --> 00:31:57.238
field of generating insight into how chromatin

541
00:31:57.298 --> 00:31:59.458
alterations are driving cancer,

542
00:32:00.558 --> 00:32:03.998
and now being able to successfully therapeutically intervene.

543
00:32:04.078 --> 00:32:07.458
So Dr. Scott Armstrong from Dana-Farber Cancer Institute.

544
00:32:13.018 --> 00:32:15.878
Thanks, Charlie, for the introduction and the invitation.

545
00:32:16.338 --> 00:32:20.048
It's really great to be on the stage with someone who we started our labs

546
00:32:20.158 --> 00:32:24.118
basically at the same time together at Dana-Farber, and also with somebody

547
00:32:24.138 --> 00:32:28.108
who spent 20 to 30% of her time anyway as a postdoctoral fellow in my lab.

548
00:32:28.468 --> 00:32:32.438
Spent most of her time learning biochemistry from the late David Allis, but in so

549
00:32:32.478 --> 00:32:35.698
doing, led an incredible collaboration between our labs. So thank you, Liling.

550
00:32:37.138 --> 00:32:40.058
So as Charlie mentioned, I'm going to talk a little bit more about the therapeutic

551
00:32:40.118 --> 00:32:40.558
side

552
00:32:41.438 --> 00:32:44.538
of some of the mechanisms that Liling just talked about.

553
00:32:44.568 --> 00:32:48.018
And in fact, her mechanistic talk is a great

554
00:32:48.058 --> 00:32:51.538
background for the MLL fusions because everything she just said about

555
00:32:51.598 --> 00:32:55.117
ENL is probably how the MLL fusions work as well.

556
00:32:55.258 --> 00:32:56.518
So that's tremendous

557
00:32:57.938 --> 00:33:00.238
background for the talk. So these are the people that have done the work.

558
00:33:00.298 --> 00:33:03.998
These are my disclosures. The only one that's relevant is menin inhibition in

559
00:33:04.098 --> 00:33:07.178
NPM1 mutant AML because I'm going to talk quite a bit about that.

560
00:33:07.738 --> 00:33:08.558
So you've heard

561
00:33:09.618 --> 00:33:12.078
a little bit from Liling about the MLL fusions.

562
00:33:13.158 --> 00:33:16.118
MLL fusion proteins schematically shown here are generated by

563
00:33:16.938 --> 00:33:19.878
translocations of the MLL or KMT2A gene.

564
00:33:19.918 --> 00:33:22.298
Those are used interchangeably.

565
00:33:23.198 --> 00:33:27.078
And when that translocation occurs, it

566
00:33:27.118 --> 00:33:30.598
generates an MLL fusion protein shown here, where the N-terminus of wild-type

567
00:33:30.718 --> 00:33:34.378
MLL is fused to the C-terminus of actually what's some 100

568
00:33:34.458 --> 00:33:38.418
different fusion proteins. But ENL, as Liling said, is one of the common ones,

569
00:33:38.578 --> 00:33:42.358
AF9 as well, AF4. All of those are members of different

570
00:33:42.378 --> 00:33:45.048
chromatin-associated complexes themselves.

571
00:33:45.638 --> 00:33:49.118
And the presence of this translocation in leukemia is

572
00:33:49.158 --> 00:33:51.578
associated with a particularly poor prognosis.

573
00:33:51.638 --> 00:33:54.198
That's what got me into it when I learned that in the late '90s.

574
00:33:54.858 --> 00:33:58.378
The clinical part was discovered in the '80s, and then the

575
00:33:58.398 --> 00:34:02.138
breakpoint was cloned by a number of groups in the early '90s to

576
00:34:02.178 --> 00:34:06.068
show that this MLL protein, the wild-type version of

577
00:34:06.078 --> 00:34:09.278
which is a 500 kilodalton nuclear protein, was the

578
00:34:09.899 --> 00:34:11.978
homolog of Drosophila Trithorax.

579
00:34:12.298 --> 00:34:15.958
Really through this C-terminal SET domain, which we now know based on David

580
00:34:15.978 --> 00:34:19.718
Allis's work, is a histone H3 lysine 4

581
00:34:19.778 --> 00:34:23.658
methyltransferase that regulates both in Drosophila

582
00:34:23.669 --> 00:34:26.859
and in mammalian cells, the HOX genes or homeotic genes that you heard about

583
00:34:27.758 --> 00:34:30.819
from Liling, and in leukemia, particularly the HOXA cluster genes.

584
00:34:32.178 --> 00:34:35.998
Dave's lab isolated this large MLL complex shown here,

585
00:34:36.919 --> 00:34:40.598
and a number of groups showed that the MLL wild-type protein

586
00:34:40.678 --> 00:34:43.808
is cleaved into an N-terminus and C-terminus.

587
00:34:43.859 --> 00:34:47.609
And suffice it to say that the MLL fusion basically is this N-terminal

588
00:34:47.678 --> 00:34:51.348
part fused to the C-terminus of many different proteins, and

589
00:34:51.379 --> 00:34:55.218
therefore you lock together a group of chromatin

590
00:34:55.298 --> 00:34:59.278
complexes that should not be locked together that way in order to drive gene

591
00:34:59.318 --> 00:35:03.058
expression. In early 2000s as well, Mike Cleary

592
00:35:03.198 --> 00:35:07.118
and Matthew Meyerson independently demonstrated that

593
00:35:07.127 --> 00:35:10.858
this protein here, menin, the product of the multiple endocrine neoplasia type

594
00:35:11.118 --> 00:35:14.808
1 gene, is found both in the wild-type MLL

595
00:35:14.898 --> 00:35:18.498
complex, that was Matthew Meyerson's work, and the ONC

596
00:35:18.598 --> 00:35:19.538
protein complex,

597
00:35:20.398 --> 00:35:24.358
Mike Cleary's work. And then in the early 2010s, Jolanta Grimbecka showed

598
00:35:24.378 --> 00:35:27.758
that actually you could make small molecules that could disrupt

599
00:35:28.038 --> 00:35:29.078
this interaction.

600
00:35:29.978 --> 00:35:33.278
And while we were working on the biology of MLL fusions, which I won't talk about

601
00:35:33.378 --> 00:35:37.098
at all really today other than in the context of menin inhibitors, we started a

602
00:35:37.138 --> 00:35:38.968
collaboration in 2014 with which

603
00:35:39.798 --> 00:35:43.358
then was called Vitae Pharmaceuticals with Gerry McGeehan,

604
00:35:43.738 --> 00:35:45.618
and then he moved to Syndax Pharmaceuticals.

605
00:35:45.648 --> 00:35:46.448
And in the process,

606
00:35:47.498 --> 00:35:51.238
they identified a very potent and selective small molecule menin

607
00:35:51.278 --> 00:35:55.168
inhibitor. And we showed mechanistically how that works is by

608
00:35:55.618 --> 00:35:58.558
disrupting the MLL menin interaction. That actually was known.

609
00:35:58.608 --> 00:36:00.178
That was what it was supposed to do.

610
00:36:00.218 --> 00:36:03.938
But when it does that, the MLL fusion actually comes off of chromatin at

611
00:36:04.018 --> 00:36:07.918
very selected loci. Getting back a little bit to the discussion about loci

612
00:36:07.938 --> 00:36:11.638
selectivity and how that works, continuing to work on that.

613
00:36:11.658 --> 00:36:15.598
But certain MLL fusion loci and wild-type MLL

614
00:36:15.608 --> 00:36:19.378
loci are very dependent on menin to remain bound to chromatin, and it's

615
00:36:19.438 --> 00:36:23.248
those genes that get repressed whenever you treat with an MLL

616
00:36:23.378 --> 00:36:24.138
menin inhibitor.

617
00:36:24.998 --> 00:36:28.158
Here's the VTB-50469 we published in 2019.

618
00:36:28.258 --> 00:36:32.038
You move one methyl group and you have what is now called revumenib.

619
00:36:33.458 --> 00:36:36.838
And while doing this, we also were able to show that both in

620
00:36:37.358 --> 00:36:41.158
NPM1 mutant AMLs, which many of you probably know are way more common than

621
00:36:41.258 --> 00:36:45.058
MLL fusion rearranged AMLs, and in a rare

622
00:36:45.158 --> 00:36:48.858
but deadly subtype of pediatric AML, those with nucleoporin

623
00:36:49.038 --> 00:36:52.398
98 rearrangements, very similar mechanisms are at play.

624
00:36:52.598 --> 00:36:56.338
The mutant nucleophosmin actually binds toHOX loci,

625
00:36:56.378 --> 00:36:56.888
MEIS1,

626
00:36:57.998 --> 00:37:01.918
after it's mutated, and it's dependent on MLL menin interaction in

627
00:37:01.958 --> 00:37:05.338
order to maintain that expression, and essentially the NUP98 fusion

628
00:37:05.898 --> 00:37:09.618
works very similarly. And with these three mutations, this accounts for

629
00:37:09.658 --> 00:37:13.508
about 40% of all AML cases in both adults and

630
00:37:13.598 --> 00:37:17.538
children. And perhaps the most exciting part of this in the past

631
00:37:17.578 --> 00:37:21.538
year and a half or two years, the FDA has approved revumenib for the

632
00:37:21.598 --> 00:37:24.818
treatment of relapsed/refractory KMT2A rearranged

633
00:37:24.918 --> 00:37:27.917
AML and NPM1 AML in

634
00:37:28.298 --> 00:37:32.278
2024 and 2025 respectively, and ziftomenib from

635
00:37:32.298 --> 00:37:36.058
Cure Oncology for NPM1 mutant AML also in

636
00:37:36.198 --> 00:37:39.708
2025. So these now are definitely being given to patients,

637
00:37:40.538 --> 00:37:44.128
at least in the United States. Hopefully approvals to follow soon in other

638
00:37:44.158 --> 00:37:48.018
parts of the country. But as you might imagine, with any single-agent

639
00:37:48.028 --> 00:37:51.758
targeted therapy, there's always the possibility of the development of

640
00:37:51.778 --> 00:37:55.747
resistance. Having said that, this was at least one of the first, if not

641
00:37:55.778 --> 00:37:59.598
the first protein-protein interaction inhibitor that was targeting

642
00:37:59.678 --> 00:38:03.578
chromatin, so we didn't really know exactly what to expect in terms of how

643
00:38:03.618 --> 00:38:07.598
the cells would mutate themselves, adapt, in order to

644
00:38:07.618 --> 00:38:11.198
become what we presumed would be resistant to the small molecule.

645
00:38:12.098 --> 00:38:15.778
So the first type of mutational resistance we described, I'm going to go through

646
00:38:15.818 --> 00:38:18.398
quickly because this is published, so I can get into the other stuff.

647
00:38:19.018 --> 00:38:22.248
But basically using base editor screens, PDX models,

648
00:38:22.478 --> 00:38:26.248
and samples from patients that were sequenced at Memorial

649
00:38:26.258 --> 00:38:29.398
Sloan Kettering, we were able to show that indeed,

650
00:38:30.038 --> 00:38:33.998
mutation of the small molecule binding pocket is a very common

651
00:38:34.078 --> 00:38:36.858
form of resistant to single-agent therapy.

652
00:38:37.198 --> 00:38:40.118
These are the mutations that we've described as the most common.

653
00:38:40.218 --> 00:38:44.138
We definitely are seeing these now in patients with some

654
00:38:44.638 --> 00:38:48.228
frequency, and this methionine 327 being the one that

655
00:38:48.258 --> 00:38:52.078
affects most of the inhibitors. There are actually now some five or six

656
00:38:52.118 --> 00:38:52.738
being developed,

657
00:38:53.578 --> 00:38:57.158
and this G331 also being particularly difficult to deal with.

658
00:38:57.818 --> 00:39:01.638
All of the mutations shift the IC50s for the small molecule and

659
00:39:02.978 --> 00:39:05.818
affect the affinities of the small molecules for their binding.

660
00:39:06.618 --> 00:39:10.398
These mutations are found in patients with MLL rearranged and NPM1

661
00:39:10.438 --> 00:39:14.378
mutant AML. That's important because, as I said, it wasn't so clear, at least

662
00:39:14.418 --> 00:39:17.298
at the time, if the NPM1 mutant AML was being

663
00:39:17.358 --> 00:39:20.318
driven by menin.

664
00:39:20.938 --> 00:39:24.318
And interestingly enough, we published soon a paper

665
00:39:24.338 --> 00:39:27.918
showing the full landscape of mutations that can lead to

666
00:39:27.938 --> 00:39:31.858
resistance to the five different clinical inhibitors, and as you might

667
00:39:31.898 --> 00:39:35.158
imagine from a structural standpoint, the mutations are not all the same, and you

668
00:39:35.178 --> 00:39:38.538
can actually get one to work in the context of the

669
00:39:38.598 --> 00:39:39.458
mutation

670
00:39:41.598 --> 00:39:45.518
that was generated in the presence

671
00:39:45.578 --> 00:39:47.518
of one of the other inhibitors. Sorry.

672
00:39:48.958 --> 00:39:52.898
So of course, combination therapies are one way

673
00:39:53.178 --> 00:39:56.378
to deal with this, but the important from a biological standpoint

674
00:39:58.018 --> 00:40:01.898
here is that this really does validate menin as a therapeutic target when

675
00:40:02.038 --> 00:40:05.238
the cancers go to this amount of trouble to mutate themselves.

676
00:40:06.918 --> 00:40:08.658
However, I've told you that

677
00:40:09.518 --> 00:40:12.578
the way that this resistance develops, it's not an absolute resistance.

